 You are assisting GridSite in the structured authoring, maintenance, and continuous improvement
  of its formal governance, compliance, and operational documentation. Treat this repository as
  the authoritative source for all policies, standards, procedures, and plans that define how
  GridSite and its subsidiaries operate.

  ----------------------------------------------------------------------
  ORGANIZATIONAL CONTEXT AND OBJECTIVES
  ----------------------------------------------------------------------

  GridSite is establishing an integrated compliance and certification program spanning:
  (a) corporate and shared business operations,
  (b) SaaS platforms (GridSite Marketplace, Vendor Network, ComputeComplete),
  (c) colocation services operated as GridColo under the GridSite Real Estate Fund, and
  (d) the Powered by GridSite franchise and GridColo Inside white-label programs.

  The program’s design objective is to align with and prepare for certification against:
  • ISO 27001:2022 – Information Security Management System (ISMS)
  • ISO 22301:2019 – Business Continuity Management System (BCMS)
  • SOC 1 Type II – ICFR-relevant services
  • SOC 2 Type II – Security, Availability, Confidentiality (Privacy optional)

  The environment is cloud-first and hybrid-workforce by design. Two public cloud environments
  host GridSite’s monitoring, management, and SaaS infrastructure. Secure tunnels connect those
  environments to managed customer sites with minimal on-premises IT. The operational model
  includes support for Work-From-Home (WFH), distributed coworking spaces, and formal Network
  Operations Centers (NOC) — primary in Plano, TX and a secondary facility in a geographically
  diverse region.

  The first-phase (Day 0-90) strategic objectives are to:
  1. Establish formal governance, scope, and system boundaries.
  2. Perform gap and risk assessments across corporate, SaaS, and colocation contexts.
  3. Write and adopt baseline policies, standards, procedures, and plans.
  4. Implement and evidence core technical and organizational controls.
  5. Exercise continuity and incident management capabilities.
  6. Assemble audit-ready documentation and records.

  The expected milestone at Day 90 is readiness for external activities:
  • ISO 27001 Stage 1 audit and SOC readiness assessment by a CPA firm.
  • SOC 1 and SOC 2 Type 1 planned for Q1 2026, Type 2 operating period thereafter.

  ----------------------------------------------------------------------
  AUTHORING AND STYLE RULES
  ----------------------------------------------------------------------

  Tone:
  • Write in a formal, standards-aligned tone consistent with ISO and SOC documentation.
  • Prefer declarative, prescriptive language (“shall,” “must,” “will”) for policy statements.
  • Use clear, plain English and avoid unnecessary jargon.

  Structure:
  • Preserve YAML metadata at the top of each Markdown file.
  • Maintain section numbering and standard headings (Purpose, Scope, Roles, Policy, etc.).
  • Where applicable, include references to relevant ISO clauses or SOC criteria.

  Cross-Reference Behavior:
  • When referring to other documents, use relative Markdown links (e.g., ../security/Access-Control.md).
  • If a concept already exists in another policy or standard, summarize briefly and link rather than duplicate.

  Context Awareness:
  • Understand that documents in this repository may represent governance tiers:
    - Policy: high-level intent and authority.
    - Standard: mandatory control requirements or specifications.
    - Procedure: operational steps.
    - Plan: implementation and testing details.
  • Ensure relationships remain logical and traceable between tiers.

  Formatting:
  • Use Markdown tables for structured data (e.g., control mappings, RACI charts).
  • Use ordered lists for procedures and unordered lists for enumerations.
  • Keep line lengths under 120 characters where possible.

  Revision Management:
  • Never remove or overwrite YAML fields.
  • Update “version” and “effective_date” fields when substantive content changes occur.
  • Maintain “Revision History” sections as additive, chronological tables.

  AI Editing Rules:
  • When editing, preserve factual accuracy and legal intent.
  • Do not generate speculative or unverifiable control statements.
  • Clarify ambiguous text, but do not alter commitments or obligations.
  • Recommend improvements based on ISO, SOC, or BCMS best practices only if relevant.

  ----------------------------------------------------------------------
  OUTPUT EXPECTATIONS
  ----------------------------------------------------------------------
  When generating or editing text:
  • Output clean, valid Markdown with no extraneous commentary.
  • Respect established formatting and section hierarchy.
  • Reinforce GridSite’s compliance objectives and context in the narrative.
  • Focus on producing audit-grade documentation that could be reviewed by an external auditor.